**classList.toggle() - Smart Class Switching**

**üéØ What is classList.toggle()?**
The `classList.toggle()` method is a convenient way to add or remove a CSS class from an element. It automatically checks if the class exists and toggles it on/off.

**üîÑ Basic Syntax:**
```javascript
element.classList.toggle('className');
```

**üìñ How It Works:**
```javascript
const button = document.querySelector('.my-button');

// Toggle the 'active' class
button.classList.toggle('active');

// First click: adds 'active' class
// <button class="my-button active">Click me</button>

// Second click: removes 'active' class  
// <button class="my-button">Click me</button>

// Third click: adds 'active' class again
// And so on...
```

**üé® Practical Examples:**

**Toggle Menu Visibility:**
```html
<button class="menu-toggle" onclick="toggleMenu()">‚ò∞ Menu</button>
<nav class="main-nav" id="mainNav">
  <a href="#home">Home</a>
  <a href="#about">About</a>
  <a href="#contact">Contact</a>
</nav>

<script>
function toggleMenu() {
  const nav = document.getElementById('mainNav');
  nav.classList.toggle('nav-open');
}
</script>

<style>
.main-nav {
  display: none;
}

.main-nav.nav-open {
  display: block;
}
</style>
```

**Dark/Light Mode Toggle:**
```javascript
function toggleDarkMode() {
  document.body.classList.toggle('dark-mode');

  // Update button text
  const button = document.querySelector('.theme-toggle');
  if (document.body.classList.contains('dark-mode')) {
    button.textContent = '‚òÄÔ∏è Light Mode';
  } else {
    button.textContent = 'üåô Dark Mode';
  }
}
```

**Accordion/Collapsible Sections:**
```html
<div class="accordion">
  <button class="accordion-header" onclick="toggleSection(this)">
    Section 1
    <span class="arrow">‚ñº</span>
  </button>
  <div class="accordion-content">
    <p>This content can be shown/hidden.</p>
  </div>
</div>

<script>
function toggleSection(header) {
  const content = header.nextElementSibling;
  content.classList.toggle('active');
  header.classList.toggle('active');
}
</script>

<style>
.accordion-content {
  display: none;
}

.accordion-content.active {
  display: block;
}

.accordion-header.active .arrow {
  transform: rotate(180deg);
}
</style>
```

**üõ†Ô∏è Advanced Toggle Features:**

**Force State (Add/Remove):**
```javascript
const element = document.querySelector('.my-element');

// Force add (like add() but returns true)
element.classList.toggle('active', true);  // Always adds

// Force remove (like remove() but returns false)  
element.classList.toggle('active', false); // Always removes

// Normal toggle (automatic)
element.classList.toggle('active');        // Toggles based on current state
```

**Check Current State:**
```javascript
function isElementActive(element) {
  return element.classList.contains('active');
}

// Toggle with condition
if (isElementActive(myButton)) {
  console.log('Button is currently active');
}
```

**Multiple Classes:**
```javascript
// Toggle multiple classes at once
function toggleMultipleClasses(element, ...classNames) {
  classNames.forEach(className => {
    element.classList.toggle(className);
  });
}

// Usage
toggleMultipleClasses(menu, 'open', 'animated', 'visible');
```

**üéØ Real-World Use Cases:**

**Favorite/Bookmark Toggle:**
```javascript
function toggleFavorite(bookId) {
  const heartIcon = document.querySelector(`[data-book="${bookId}"]`);
  heartIcon.classList.toggle('favorited');

  // Update icon
  if (heartIcon.classList.contains('favorited')) {
    heartIcon.textContent = '‚ù§Ô∏è';
  } else {
    heartIcon.textContent = 'ü§ç';
  }
}
```

**Form Validation States:**
```javascript
function validateEmail(input) {
  const isValid = input.value.includes('@');
  input.classList.toggle('valid', isValid);
  input.classList.toggle('invalid', !isValid);
}
```

**Tab System:**
```javascript
function switchTab(tabId) {
  // Remove active from all tabs
  document.querySelectorAll('.tab').forEach(tab => {
    tab.classList.remove('active');
  });

  // Add active to clicked tab
  document.getElementById(tabId).classList.add('active');
}

// Using toggle for simpler implementation
function toggleTab(tabId) {
  const tab = document.getElementById(tabId);
  tab.classList.toggle('active');
}
```

**üìä Toggle vs Add/Remove:**

```javascript
// Traditional approach
if (element.classList.contains('active')) {
  element.classList.remove('active');
} else {
  element.classList.add('active');
}

// Modern approach (same result)
element.classList.toggle('active');
```

**üí° Best Practices:**
1. **Use descriptive class names** like `is-open`, `is-active`, `is-visible`
2. **Combine with CSS transitions** for smooth animations
3. **Consider accessibility** - update ARIA attributes when toggling
4. **Use data attributes** to store state if needed
5. **Test both states** - make sure both on/off states work properly

**üîß CSS Transition Example:**
```css
.menu {
  transform: translateX(-100%);
  transition: transform 0.3s ease;
}

.menu.is-open {
  transform: translateX(0);
}

.button {
  background: blue;
  transition: background 0.2s;
}

.button.is-active {
  background: green;
}
```

**Summary:** `classList.toggle()` is perfect for any feature that switches between two states - it's cleaner, more readable, and less error-prone than manually checking and adding/removing classes.

**JavaScript Random Numbers - Complete Guide**

**üé≤ Basic Random Generation:**

**Random Decimal (0 to 1):**
```javascript
Math.random()  // Returns: 0.0 to 0.9999... (1 is exclusive)
// Examples: 0.123, 0.789, 0.456
```

**Random Whole Number (0 to max-1):**
```javascript
// Random from 0 to 9
Math.floor(Math.random() * 10)

// Random from 0 to 99  
Math.floor(Math.random() * 100)
```

**üî¢ Random Number in Range (min to max):**

**Inclusive Range Function:**
```javascript
function getRandomInRange(min, max) {
  return Math.floor(Math.random() * (max - min + 1)) + min;
}

// Examples:
getRandomInRange(1, 10);   // 1, 2, 3, ..., 10
getRandomInRange(5, 15);   // 5, 6, 7, ..., 15
getRandomInRange(-5, 5);   // -5, -4, ..., 4, 5
```

**Formula Breakdown:**
```javascript
// Step-by-step for range 5-15:
Math.random()                     // 0.0 to 0.999...
* (15 - 5 + 1)                    // * 11 ‚Üí 0.0 to 10.999...
Math.floor(...)                   // 0 to 10 (integer)
+ 5                               // 5 to 15 ‚úì
```

**üö´ Excluding Zero (Never Generate 0):**
```javascript
// Random from 1 to max (never 0)
function getRandomNonZero(max) {
  return Math.floor(Math.random() * max) + 1;
}

getRandomNonZero(10);  // 1, 2, 3, ..., 10 (never 0)
getRandomNonZero(6);   // 1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6 (dice roll)
```

**üìä Random Array Elements:**

**Random Element from Array:**
```javascript
const fruits = ['üçé', 'üçå', 'üçí', 'üçä', 'üçá'];

// Get random fruit
const randomFruit = fruits[Math.floor(Math.random() * fruits.length)];
console.log(randomFruit); // üçå (random each time)
```

**Multiple Random Elements:**
```javascript
function getRandomElements(array, count) {
  const shuffled = [...array].sort(() => 0.5 - Math.random());
  return shuffled.slice(0, count);
}

const colors = ['red', 'blue', 'green', 'yellow', 'purple'];
getRandomElements(colors, 3); // ['blue', 'red', 'yellow'] (random)
```

**üéØ Practical Examples:**

**Dice Roll Simulator:**
```javascript
function rollDice() {
  return Math.floor(Math.random() * 6) + 1;  // 1-6
}

console.log(`You rolled: ${rollDice()}`); // "You rolled: 4"
```

**Random Color Generator:**
```javascript
function getRandomColor() {
  const colors = ['red', 'blue', 'green', 'yellow', 'purple', 'orange'];
  return colors[Math.floor(Math.random() * colors.length)];
}

document.body.style.backgroundColor = getRandomColor();
```

**Random Password Character:**
```javascript
function getRandomChar() {
  const chars = 'ABCDEFGHIJKLMNOPQRSTUVWXYZabcdefghijklmnopqrstuvwxyz0123456789';
  return chars[Math.floor(Math.random() * chars.length)];
}

console.log(getRandomChar()); // "k" (random character)
```

**Lottery Number Generator:**
```javascript
function generateLotteryNumbers(max, count) {
  const numbers = [];
  while (numbers.length < count) {
    const num = Math.floor(Math.random() * max) + 1;
    if (!numbers.includes(num)) {
      numbers.push(num);
    }
  }
  return numbers.sort((a, b) => a - b);
}

generateLotteryNumbers(49, 6); // [5, 12, 23, 34, 41, 49] (random)
```

**üîÑ Alternative Methods:**

**Using Crypto (More Secure Random):**
```javascript
// For cryptographic purposes
function getSecureRandom(max) {
  const randomBuffer = new Uint32Array(1);
  window.crypto.getRandomValues(randomBuffer);
  return randomBuffer[0] % max;
}
```

**Random Boolean:**
```javascript
const randomBool = Math.random() >= 0.5;  // true or false
```

**Random with Decimals:**
```javascript
function getRandomFloat(min, max) {
  return Math.random() * (max - min) + min;
}

getRandomFloat(1.5, 5.5); // 3.214 (random decimal)
```

**üìù Common Patterns Reference:**

```javascript
// 0 to N-1
Math.floor(Math.random() * N)

// 1 to N (no zero)
Math.floor(Math.random() * N) + 1

// Min to Max (inclusive)
Math.floor(Math.random() * (Max - Min + 1)) + Min

// Random array element
array[Math.floor(Math.random() * array.length)]

// Random true/false
Math.random() >= 0.5
```

**‚ö†Ô∏è Important Notes:**
- `Math.random()` is **pseudo-random** - not suitable for cryptography
- The range is **inclusive of min, exclusive of max** in floating point
- Use `Math.floor()` for integers, not `Math.round()` (biased distribution)
- For games/casino apps, consider more secure random number generators

**Performance Tip:** If you need many random numbers, generate them in batches rather than one at a time.

