A React component can only return **one root element**. Returning multiple top-level elements causes an error.

‚ùå This does NOT work:
```javascript
const App = () => {
  return (
    <h1>Hello</h1>
    <p>Welcome!</p>
  )
}
```
React says: ‚ÄúI don‚Äôt know which one is the main element!‚Äù

**How to fix:**
1. Wrap elements in a parent container:
```javascript
const App = () => {
  return (
    <div>
      <h1>Hello</h1>
      <p>Welcome!</p>
    </div>
  )
}
```
2. Use a React Fragment (no extra HTML added):
```javascript
import React from 'react'

const App = () => {
  return (
    <>
      <h1>Hello</h1>
      <p>Welcome!</p>
    </>
  )
}
```
`<> ... </>` acts as a ‚Äúghost box‚Äù: React sees one root, but no extra `<div>` is added to the HTML. Clean and lightweight.

You can have multiple `return` statements in a component using conditional logic. Only the first `return` that runs will execute.

Example:
```javascript
const loggedIn = true;

if (loggedIn) {
  return <h1>Hello Member</h1>; // 1st return
}

return (
  <>
    <div>
      {loggedIn ? <h1>Hello Member</h1> : <h1>Hello Guest</h1>}
    </div>
  </>
); // 2nd return
```
If the first `return` runs, the second won't. It's recommended to structure your logic with conditionals to decide which return to execute.

