To use components in React, you need to **export** them from their file and **import** them where you want to use them.

**Steps:**
1. Create a component in a file inside the `components` folder (e.g., `Navbar.jsx`). You can use the VS Code shortcut `rafce` to generate an arrow function component template.
```javascript
// Navbar.jsx
import React from 'react';

const Navbar = () => {
  return (
    <nav>
      <h1>My Navbar</h1>
    </nav>
  );
}

export default Navbar;
```
2. In your main file (e.g., `App.jsx`), import the component:
```javascript
import Navbar from './components/Navbar';
```
3. Use the component in JSX:
```jsx
<Navbar />
```
**Note:** Component names must start with a **capital letter**.

Props (short for "properties") are values you pass from a parent component to a child component. They make components dynamic and reusable.

**Example with `<Hero />` component:**
```javascript
// Hero.jsx (child component)
const Hero = (props) => {
  return (
    <div>
      <h1>{props.title}</h1>
      <p>{props.subtitle}</p>
    </div>
  );
}
export default Hero;

// App.jsx (parent component)
import Hero from './components/Hero';

const App = () => {
  return (
    <div>
      <Hero title="Test Title" subtitle="This is a subtitle" />
    </div>
  );
}
export default App;
```
- `props.title` ‚Üí "Test Title"
- `props.subtitle` ‚Üí "This is a subtitle"

**Destructuring props for cleaner code:**
```javascript
const Hero = ({ title, subtitle }) => {
  return (
    <div>
      <h1>{title}</h1>
      <p>{subtitle}</p>
    </div>
  );
}
```
**Destructuring with default values:**
```javascript
const Hero = ({ title = 'This is the default title', subtitle = 'Default subtitle' }) => {
  return (
    <div>
      <h1>{title}</h1>
      <p>{subtitle}</p>
    </div>
  );
}
```
- If the parent passes props, they override defaults.
- If the parent does not pass props, default values are used.

Wrapping means putting one piece of content inside a component so that the component can automatically add styles, structure, or behavior. The content inside becomes `children` of that component.

**Example:**
```javascript
// Card.jsx
const Card = ({ children }) => {
  return (
    <div className="bg-blue-200 p-4 rounded-lg shadow-md">
      {children}
    </div>
  );
}
export default Card;

// App.jsx
import Card from './components/Card';

const App = () => {
  return (
    <div>
      <Card>
        <h1>Hello!</h1>
        <p>This is a wrapped paragraph.</p>
      </Card>

      <Card>
        <button>Click Me</button>
      </Card>
    </div>
  );
}
export default App;
```
**Result:** The `<h1>` and `<p>` inherit the Card styling; the `<button>` inside the second Card also inherits the same styling. ‚úÖ

Think of `useState` as a special box to store a value in React. You can change the value anytime, and React will automatically update the UI.

**Example: Counter**
```javascript
import { useState } from 'react';

const Counter = () => {
  const [count, setCount] = useState(0); // count = current value, setCount = function to update it

  return (
    <div>
      <h1>Count: {count}</h1>
      <button onClick={() => setCount(count + 1)}>Increase</button>
    </div>
  );
};
export default Counter;
```
- `count` ‚Üí current value
- `setCount` ‚Üí updates the value
- React automatically re-renders the component when the value changes.

