- First argument: function that returns a value
- Second argument: array of dependencies
- React recomputes only when dependencies change, optimizing performance.

You can loop through all expenses, compare each expense's date to today's date using getFullYear(), getMonth(), and getDate(), then update running totals stored in React state.

**Example:**
```javascript
import React, { useState, useEffect } from 'react';

function ExpenseSummary({ expenses }) {
  const [totals, setTotals] = useState({
    totalToday: 0,
    totalThisMonth: 0,
    totalThisYear: 0,
  });

  useEffect(() => {
    const today = new Date();
    const newTotals = { totalToday: 0, totalThisMonth: 0, totalThisYear: 0 };

    expenses.forEach(({ amount, date }) => {
      const expenseDate = new Date(date);

      const isSameYear = expenseDate.getFullYear() === today.getFullYear();
      if (!isSameYear) return;

      newTotals.totalThisYear += amount;

      const isSameMonth = expenseDate.getMonth() === today.getMonth();
      if (isSameMonth) {
        newTotals.totalThisMonth += amount;

        const isSameDay = expenseDate.getDate() === today.getDate();
        if (isSameDay) newTotals.totalToday += amount;
      }
    });

    setTotals(newTotals);
  }, [expenses]);

  return (
    <section>
      <h3>Expense Summary</h3>
      <p>Today: ${totals.totalToday}</p>
      <p>This Month: ${totals.totalThisMonth}</p>
      <p>This Year: ${totals.totalThisYear}</p>
    </section>
  );
}

export default ExpenseSummary;
```

**Explanation:**
- **useEffect:** Recalculates totals whenever the expenses array changes.
- **getFullYear, getMonth, getDate:** Used to compare each expense‚Äôs date with today.
- **isSameYear ‚Üí isSameMonth ‚Üí isSameDay:** Nested checks ensure proper totals without unnecessary calculations.
- **setTotals:** Updates the component‚Äôs state, triggering a re-render to show fresh totals.

This pattern is great for dashboards or expense trackers that need daily, monthly, and yearly summaries automatically recalculated when new data arrives.

You can compare different parts of a Date object using getFullYear(), getMonth(), and getDate(). This helps categorize data by year, month, or day.

**Example:**
```javascript
const isSameYear = expenseDate.getFullYear() === today.getFullYear();
if (!isSameYear) return;

totals.totalThisYear += amount;

const isSameMonth = expenseDate.getMonth() === today.getMonth() && isSameYear;
if (isSameMonth) {
  totals.totalThisMonth += amount;

  const isSameDay = expenseDate.getDate() === today.getDate();
  if (isSameDay) {
    totals.totalToday += amount;
  }
}
```

**Explanation:**
- **getFullYear():** Checks if both dates are in the same year.
- **getMonth():** Checks if they are in the same month (0‚Äì11).
- **getDate():** Checks if they fall on the same day of the month.

**Logic:**
- If the expense is in the same year ‚Üí add to yearly total.
- If it‚Äôs also in the same month ‚Üí add to monthly total.
- If it‚Äôs also the same day ‚Üí add to today‚Äôs total.

This layered check ensures each level (year ‚Üí month ‚Üí day) only runs when the previous one matches, keeping the code efficient and readable.

React Hooks must follow strict rules so React can track them correctly.

1Ô∏è‚É£ **Hooks must run in the same order every render**
React tracks hooks by their position, not their name. If you change the order, the component breaks.
Example order React expects:
- Hook #1 ‚Üí useState
- Hook #2 ‚Üí useEffect
- Hook #3 ‚Üí useMemo

2Ô∏è‚É£ **Never call hooks inside conditions**
‚ùå Bad:
```javascript
if (isLoggedIn) {
  useState(0); // skipped sometimes ‚Üí breaks
}
```
Hooks get skipped when the condition is false ‚Üí React loses track.

3Ô∏è‚É£ **Never call hooks inside loops or nested functions**
‚ùå Bad:
```javascript
for (...) {
  useEffect(() => {});
}
```
‚ùå Bad:
```javascript
function doSomething() {
  useState(5);
}
```
Hooks ONLY work inside:
- React component functions
- Custom hooks

4Ô∏è‚É£ **Hooks must run before any early return**
‚úî Safe:
```javascript
const [a, setA] = useState(0);
const [b, setB] = useState(1);
if (!ready) return null;
```
‚ùå Not safe:
```javascript
if (!ready) return null;
useState(0); // sometimes skipped
```

5Ô∏è‚É£ **You can write hooks in any order ‚Äî just keep them consistent**
This is valid:
```javascript
useEffect(...);
useState(...);
useMemo(...);
useCallback(...);
```
React doesn't care about your writing order ‚Äî it ONLY cares that the order never changes between renders.

‚úî Good Example:
```javascript
function Profile({ user }) {
  const [count, setCount] = useState(0);  // hook #1
  const [theme, setTheme] = useState('light'); // hook #2

  useEffect(() => {
    console.log('User updated');
  }, [user]); // hook #3

  return <div>{user.name}</div>;
}
```

‚ùå Bad Example:
```javascript
function Profile({ user }) {
  if (!user) return null; // ‚ùå early return before hooks

  const [count, setCount] = useState(0);

  if (count > 5) {
    useEffect(() => {}, []); // ‚ùå hook inside condition
  }

  return <div>Hi</div>;
}
```

‚≠ê Summary:
- Hooks must run in the SAME order on every render
- Put hooks at the top of your component
- No hooks inside conditions, loops, or nested functions
- No hooks after early returns

A custom hook is a reusable function that uses React's built-in hooks to share logic between components.

üîπ **Starts with `use`** (example: useCounter, useFetch)
üîπ **Can use any hook** (useState, useEffect, useMemo, etc.)
üîπ **Does NOT return JSX** ‚Äî it only returns data or functions
üîπ **Called inside components just like built-in hooks**

Example ‚Äî simple custom hook:
```javascript
