**Event Propagation & Delegation - Complete Guide**

**üîÑ Event Propagation (Event Flow):**
Event propagation describes how events travel through the DOM tree. It has three phases:

**1. Capturing Phase (Trickle Down):**
- Event travels from the **window ‚Üí document ‚Üí body ‚Üí parent ‚Üí target**
- Moves from outermost ancestor down to the target element
- Rarely used in practice

**2. Target Phase:**
- Event reaches the **exact element** that was clicked/triggered
- This is where the main event handling occurs

**3. Bubbling Phase (Bubble Up):**
- Event travels back up from **target ‚Üí parent ‚Üí body ‚Üí document ‚Üí window**
- Moves from target element up to outermost ancestor
- **This is the default behavior**

**Visual Example:**
```html
<div class="grandparent">
  <div class="parent">
    <button class="child">Click Me</button>
  </div>
</div>

<script>
// Event propagation demonstration
document.querySelector('.grandparent').addEventListener('click', () => {
  console.log('Grandparent clicked (bubbling)');
});

document.querySelector('.parent').addEventListener('click', () => {
  console.log('Parent clicked (bubbling)');
});

document.querySelector('.child').addEventListener('click', () => {
  console.log('Child clicked (target)');
});

// When button is clicked, console shows:
// "Child clicked (target)"
// "Parent clicked (bubbling)"  
// "Grandparent clicked (bubbling)"
</script>
```

**üéØ Event Delegation (Smart Event Handling):**
Event delegation uses event bubbling to handle events efficiently by attaching a single listener to a parent element.

**Traditional Approach (Inefficient):**
```javascript
// ‚ùå Multiple listeners for similar elements
document.querySelector('.item1').addEventListener('click', handleClick);
document.querySelector('.item2').addEventListener('click', handleClick);
document.querySelector('.item3').addEventListener('click', handleClick);
// ... and so on for each item
```

**Delegation Approach (Efficient):**
```javascript
// ‚úÖ Single listener on parent
document.querySelector('.item-list').addEventListener('click', function(e) {
  // Check if the clicked element is an item
  if (e.target.classList.contains('item')) {
    console.log(`Item ${e.target.dataset.id} clicked!`);
    e.target.style.backgroundColor = 'yellow';
  }
});
```

**Practical Example - Dynamic List:**
```html
<ul class="shopping-list">
  <li class="item" data-id="1">Milk</li>
  <li class="item" data-id="2">Bread</li>
  <li class="item" data-id="3">Eggs</li>
</ul>

<button onclick="addNewItem()">Add Butter</button>

<script>
// Single event listener for all items (current and future)
document.querySelector('.shopping-list').addEventListener('click', function(e) {
  if (e.target.classList.contains('item')) {
    console.log(`You clicked: ${e.target.textContent} (ID: ${e.target.dataset.id})`);
    e.target.classList.toggle('completed');
  }
});

// New items automatically work with existing listener
function addNewItem() {
  const list = document.querySelector('.shopping-list');
  const newItem = document.createElement('li');
  newItem.className = 'item';
  newItem.dataset.id = Date.now();
  newItem.textContent = 'Butter';
  list.appendChild(newItem);
}
</script>
```

**üéØ Key Benefits of Event Delegation:**
- **Performance**: Single listener instead of many
- **Dynamic Elements**: Works with elements added later
- **Memory Efficient**: Less memory usage
- **Cleaner Code**: Centralized event handling

**üõ†Ô∏è Event Object Properties for Delegation:**
```javascript
element.addEventListener('click', function(e) {
  console.log(e.target);        // The actual clicked element
  console.log(e.currentTarget); // The element with the listener
  console.log(e.eventPhase);    // 1=Capturing, 2=Target, 3=Bubbling
  e.stopPropagation();         // Stop event from propagating further
  e.preventDefault();          // Prevent default browser behavior
});
```

**üí° When to Use Event Delegation:**
- Lists with many similar items
- Dynamic content that changes frequently
- Tables with interactive cells
- Navigation menus
- Any group of related elements

**Summary:** Event propagation explains **how** events travel, while event delegation is a **technique** that leverages bubbling for efficient event handling.

**Event Listeners - Complete Implementation Guide**

**üéØ Three Methods to Add Event Listeners:**

**1. Inline HTML Event Handlers (Simple but Limited):**
```html
<!-- Directly in HTML -->
<button onclick="alert('Button clicked!')">Click Me</button>

<!-- With function call -->
<button onclick="handleClick()">Call Function</button>

<!-- With parameters -->
<button onclick="greetUser('John')">Greet John</button>

<!-- Access event object -->
<button onclick="console.log(event)">Log Event</button>
```

**Pros & Cons:**
- ‚úÖ **Simple**: Easy for quick prototypes
- ‚úÖ **Direct**: No JavaScript setup required
- ‚ùå **Mixes concerns**: HTML + JavaScript together
- ‚ùå **Hard to maintain**: Difficult to update multiple elements
- ‚ùå **Limited**: Can only attach one listener per event
- ‚ùå **Global scope**: Functions must be globally available

**2. DOM Element Properties (Traditional):**
```javascript
const button = document.querySelector('.my-button');

// Assign function directly to element property
button.onclick = function() {
  alert('Button clicked via property!');
};

// Or use named function
function handleButtonClick() {
  console.log('Button was clicked');
}
button.onclick = handleButtonClick;
```

**Pros & Cons:**
- ‚úÖ **Clean separation**: HTML and JavaScript separate
- ‚úÖ **Simple syntax**: Easy to understand
- ‚ùå **Single handler**: Overwrites previous onclick handlers
- ‚ùå **Limited control**: No options for capture phase, once, etc.

**3. addEventListener() Method (Modern & Recommended):**
```javascript
const button = document.querySelector('.my-button');

// Basic usage
button.addEventListener('click', function() {
  alert('Button clicked!');
});

// With named function (RECOMMENDED)
function handleButtonClick() {
  console.log('Button clicked at:', new Date());
}
button.addEventListener('click', handleButtonClick); // Note: No parentheses!

// With arrow function
button.addEventListener('click', () => {
  console.log('Arrow function handler');
});

// Multiple events on same element
button.addEventListener('mouseover', handleHover);
button.addEventListener('mouseout', handleMouseOut);
button.addEventListener('click', handleClick);
```

**üö® CRITICAL: Don't Call the Function!**
```javascript
// ‚ùå WRONG - executes immediately
button.addEventListener('click', handleClick());

// ‚úÖ CORRECT - passes function reference
button.addEventListener('click', handleClick);
```

**üõ†Ô∏è Advanced addEventListener Features:**

**Event Object Access:**
```javascript
button.addEventListener('click', function(event) {
  console.log('Event type:', event.type);        // 'click'
  console.log('Target element:', event.target);  // The button
  console.log('Current target:', event.currentTarget); // The button
  console.log('Coordinates:', event.clientX, event.clientY);
});
```

**Event Options:**
```javascript
// Capture phase (instead of bubbling)
button.addEventListener('click', handleClick, { capture: true });

// Run once then automatically remove
button.addEventListener('click', handleClick, { once: true });

// Passive listener (better scrolling performance)
button.addEventListener('touchstart', handleTouch, { passive: true });

// Multiple options
button.addEventListener('click', handleClick, { 
  capture: false, 
  once: true, 
  passive: true 
});
```

**Removing Event Listeners:**
```javascript
// Must use named function to remove
function handleSpecificClick() {
  console.log('This will only work once');
}

button.addEventListener('click', handleSpecificClick);

// Later, remove the listener
button.removeEventListener('click', handleSpecificClick);
```

**üéØ Practical Comparison:**

**Scenario: Multiple buttons with different approaches**
```html
<button class="inline-btn" onclick="alert('Inline handler')">Inline</button>
<button class="property-btn">Property</button>
<button class="listener-btn">addEventListener</button>

<script>
// DOM Property approach
const propertyBtn = document.querySelector('.property-btn');
propertyBtn.onclick = function() {
  alert('DOM property handler');
};

// addEventListener approach (BEST PRACTICE)
const listenerBtn = document.querySelector('.listener-btn');
listenerBtn.addEventListener('click', function() {
  alert('addEventListener - most flexible');
});

// Can add multiple listeners
listenerBtn.addEventListener('click', function() {
  console.log('Second listener also fires');
});
</script>
```

**üìã Recommendation Guide:**
- **Use addEventListener()** for production code
- **Use DOM properties** for simple scripts
- **Avoid inline handlers** except for quick prototypes
- **Always use named functions** when you need to remove listeners

**Key Benefits of addEventListener():**
- ‚úÖ Multiple listeners per event
- ‚úÖ Fine control over event phase (capture/bubble)
- ‚úÖ Advanced options (once, passive)
- ‚úÖ Easy to remove specific listeners
- ‚úÖ Better performance with passive events
- ‚úÖ Industry standard practice

**The Window Object - Browser Global Environment**

**üåê What is the Window Object?**
The `window` object is the **global object** in browser-based JavaScript. It represents the entire browser window/tab and serves as the root of the DOM hierarchy.

**üîç Accessing the Window Object:**
```javascript
// Explicit access
console.log(window.innerWidth); // Viewport width

// Implicit access (window is global)
console.log(innerWidth); // Same as window.innerWidth

// Global variables become window properties
var globalVar = 'Hello';
console.log(window.globalVar); // 'Hello'

// But let/const don't become window properties
let localVar = 'Hi';
console.log(window.localVar); // undefined
```

**üõ†Ô∏è Key Window Properties & Methods:**

**Browser Information:**
