**encodeURIComponent() - URL Encoding Guide**

**üéØ What is encodeURIComponent?**
`encodeURIComponent()` is a JavaScript function that converts text into a URL-safe format by replacing special characters with percent-encoded equivalents (`%XX`). This prevents URLs from breaking when they contain problematic characters.

**üîß Basic Usage:**
```javascript
const original = "Spider Man: No Way Home";
const encoded = encodeURIComponent(original);
console.log(encoded); // "Spider%20Man%3A%20No%20Way%20Home"
```

**üìù Character Encoding Examples:**
```javascript
// Spaces become %20
encodeURIComponent("hello world");    // "hello%20world"

// Special symbols get encoded
encodeURIComponent("price=100&discount=20"); // "price%3D100%26discount%3D20"

// Unicode characters
encodeURIComponent("caf√© & r√©sum√©");  // "caf%C3%A9%20%26%20r%C3%A9sum%C3%A9"

// Problematic URL characters
encodeURIComponent("path/to/file?name=test"); // "path%2Fto%2Ffile%3Fname%3Dtest"
```

**üéØ Practical API Example:**

**Building API URLs Safely:**
```javascript
async function searchMovies(query, year) {
  // Encode user input to prevent URL issues
  const encodedQuery = encodeURIComponent(query);
  const encodedYear = encodeURIComponent(year);

  // Safe URL construction
  const url = `https://api.movies.com/search?q=${encodedQuery}&year=${encodedYear}`;

  try {
    const response = await fetch(url);
    const data = await response.json();
    return data.results;
  } catch (error) {
    console.error('Search failed:', error);
    return [];
  }
}

// Usage with special characters
searchMovies("Star Wars: The Force Awakens", 2015)
  .then(movies => console.log(movies));

// Without encoding, this would break:
// "Star Wars: The Force Awakens" ‚Üí colon and spaces break the URL
// With encoding, it becomes safe:
// "Star%20Wars%3A%20The%20Force%20Awakens"
```

**Form Data Submission:**
```javascript
async function submitUserProfile(userData) {
  const encodedName = encodeURIComponent(userData.name);
  const encodedBio = encodeURIComponent(userData.bio);

  const response = await fetch('/api/profile', {
    method: 'POST',
    headers: {
      'Content-Type': 'application/x-www-form-urlencoded',
    },
    body: `name=${encodedName}&bio=${encodedBio}`
  });

  return response.json();
}

// User input with problematic characters
submitUserProfile({
  name: "John O'Reilly",
  bio: "Loves coding & coffee! #developer"
});
```

**üÜö encodeURIComponent vs encodeURI:**

**encodeURIComponent (More Aggressive):**
```javascript
// Encodes most special characters including /, ?, =, &
encodeURIComponent("api/search?q=test"); 
// "api%2Fsearch%3Fq%3Dtest"
```

**encodeURI (Less Aggressive):**
```javascript
// Preserves URL structure characters like /, ?, =, &
encodeURI("api/search?q=test");
// "api/search?q=test" (only encodes spaces if present)
```

**When to Use Each:**
- **Use encodeURIComponent** for URL parameters, query values, form data
- **Use encodeURI** for complete URLs that you want to keep intact

**üîç Decoding URLs:**
```javascript
const encoded = "Spider%20Man%3A%20No%20Home";
const decoded = decodeURIComponent(encoded);
console.log(decoded); // "Spider Man: No Home"
```

**üéØ Real-World Scenarios:**

**Search Functionality:**
```javascript
function buildSearchURL(baseURL, filters) {
  const params = new URLSearchParams();

  Object.entries(filters).forEach(([key, value]) => {
    if (value !== null && value !== undefined) {
      params.append(key, encodeURIComponent(value.toString()));
    }
  });

  return `${baseURL}?${params.toString()}`;
}

// Usage
const searchURL = buildSearchURL('https://api.example.com/search', {
  query: "coffee & tea",
  category: "food/drink",
  price: "$10-$20",
  location: "New York, NY"
});

console.log(searchURL);
// "https://api.example.com/search?query=coffee%20%26%20tea&category=food%2Fdrink&price=%2410-%2420&location=New%20York%2C%20NY"
```

**Social Media Share Links:**
```javascript
function createShareLink(title, url) {
  const encodedTitle = encodeURIComponent(title);
  const encodedURL = encodeURIComponent(url);

  return `https://twitter.com/intent/tweet?text=${encodedTitle}&url=${encodedURL}`;
}

const shareLink = createShareLink(
  "Check out this amazing article!",
  "https://example.com/article?ref=social"
);
```

**‚ö†Ô∏è Common Mistakes:**

**Double Encoding:**
```javascript
// ‚ùå Wrong - encodes twice
const bad = encodeURIComponent(encodeURIComponent("hello & world"));
// "hello%2520%2526%2520world" (broken)

// ‚úÖ Correct - encode once
const good = encodeURIComponent("hello & world");
// "hello%20%26%20world" (correct)
```

**Encoding Complete URLs:**
```javascript
// ‚ùå Wrong - breaks the URL structure
encodeURIComponent("https://example.com/path?query=test");

// ‚úÖ Correct - encode only the dynamic parts
const base = "https://example.com/search";
const query = encodeURIComponent("coffee & tea");
const url = `${base}?q=${query}`;
```

**üí° Best Practices:**
1. **Always encode** user input before putting it in URLs
2. **Use URLSearchParams** for modern URL construction
3. **Encode individual values**, not entire URLs
4. **Decode on the server** if needed
5. **Consider validation** in addition to encoding

**Modern Alternative - URLSearchParams:**
```javascript
// Cleaner approach for URL parameters
const params = new URLSearchParams({
  query: "coffee & tea",
  category: "food/drink",
  limit: "10"
});

const url = `https://api.example.com/search?${params}`;
// Automatically handles encoding
```

**Summary:** Use `encodeURIComponent()` whenever you're inserting dynamic data into URLs to prevent broken links and security issues.

```javascript
import http from "http";

const PORT = 9000;

const server = http.createServer((req, res) => {
  res.write("Hello World");
  res.end();
});

server.listen(PORT, () => {
  console.log(`Server Running On Port ${PORT}`);
});
```

**What this Node.js code does (Simple Version):**

- `import http from "http";` - Brings in Node.js's HTTP toolkit
- `const PORT = 9000;` - Chooses the port number your server will use
- `http.createServer((req, res) => { ... })` - Creates a server that listens for requests
  - `req` = the request (what the visitor asks)
  - `res` = the response (what you answer)
- `res.write("Hello World");` - What your server sends back
- `res.end();` - Closes the conversation
- `server.listen(PORT, ...)` - Starts listening on the specified port

**Alternative approaches:**

1. Without res.write:
```javascript
res.end("Hello World");
```

2. Set headers and HTML:
```javascript
const server = http.createServer((req, res) => {
  res.setHeader('Content-Type', 'text/html');
  res.end("<h1>Hello World!</h1>");
});
```

3. Set status code:
```javascript
const server = http.createServer((req, res) => {
  res.setHeader('Content-Type', 'text/plain');
  res.statusCode = 404;
  res.end("<h1>Hello World!</h1>");
});
```

4. Set both header and status together:
```javascript
res.writeHead(200, { 'Content-Type': 'text/html' });
```

