**Simple Definition:**
Dynamic routes allow you to create URLs with changing parts, like /posts/1, /posts/2, etc., where the number can be any post ID.

**Basic Syntax:**
```javascript
app.get("/posts/:id", (req, res) => {
  const postId = req.params.id;  // Gets the ID from URL
  // Your code to find and return the post
});
```

**Complete Example:**
```javascript
// Sample posts data
const posts = [
  { id: 1, title: "First Post", content: "Hello world!" },
  { id: 2, title: "Second Post", content: "Learning Express" },
  { id: 3, title: "Third Post", content: "Dynamic routes are cool" }
];

// Dynamic route for individual posts
app.get("/posts/:id", (req, res) => {
  const postId = parseInt(req.params.id);  // Convert string to number
  const post = posts.find(p => p.id === postId);  // Find post by ID

  if (post) {
    res.json(post);  // Return the post if found
  } else {
    res.status(404).json({ error: "Post not found" });
  }
});
```

**How URLs Work:**
- `/posts/1` ‚Üí Returns post with ID 1
- `/posts/2` ‚Üí Returns post with ID 2
- `/posts/3` ‚Üí Returns post with ID 3
- `/posts/999` ‚Üí Returns "Post not found" error

**Multiple Parameters:**
```javascript
app.get("/users/:userId/posts/:postId", (req, res) => {
  const userId = req.params.userId;
  const postId = req.params.postId;
  // Handle the request
});
```

**Key Points:**
- `:id` is a URL parameter that can be any value
- Access it with `req.params.id`
- Always convert to number if needed (`parseInt()`)
- Add error handling for invalid IDs

**Key Idea:** Dynamic routes let you create flexible URLs that can handle different IDs or values in the URL path.

**Simple Definition:**
When you send a response (like `res.json()` or `res.send()`), the function doesn't automatically stop. You need to use `return` to prevent sending multiple responses.

**Without Return (Problem):**
```javascript
if (post) {
  res.json(post);
} 
// Code continues running here!
res.status(404).json({ error: "Not found" });
// This will ALWAYS run ‚Üí ERROR! (Can't send multiple responses)
```

**With Return (Solution):**
```javascript
if (post) {
  return res.json(post);  // Stops here if post exists
} 
res.status(404).json({ error: "Not found" });  // Only runs if no post
```

**Or Use Else:**
```javascript
if (post) {
  res.json(post);
} else {
  res.status(404).json({ error: "Not found" });
}
// Both paths are separate - no multiple responses
```

**Why This Matters:**
- Express will throw an error if you try to send multiple responses
- Without `return`, both response statements might execute
- This is a common source of bugs in Express applications

**Key Idea:**
Use `return` after sending a response to stop the function execution, otherwise Express will try to send multiple responses and crash.

**Simple Definition:**
Splitting routes means organizing your API endpoints into different files instead of having all routes in one main file.

**Step 1: Create the Main Server File (server.js)**
```javascript
const express = require("express");
const postsRouter = require("./routes/posts"); // Import router
const app = express();

// Use the router with base path
app.use('/api/posts', postsRouter);

app.listen(3000, () => {
  console.log("Server running");
});
```

**Step 2: Create Routes Folder & File (routes/posts.js)**
```javascript
const express = require("express");
const router = express.Router(); // Create router instance

// Sample data
const posts = [
  { id: 1, title: "First Post" },
  { id: 2, title: "Second Post" }
];

// Define routes WITHOUT the base path
router.get("/", (req, res) => {
  // Handles: GET /api/posts
  res.json(posts);
});

router.get("/:id", (req, res) => {
  // Handles: GET /api/posts/5
  const post = posts.find(p => p.id === parseInt(req.params.id));
  if (post) {
    res.json(post);
  } else {
    res.status(404).json({ error: "Post not found" });
  }
});

module.exports = router; // Export the router
```

**Key Rules for Splitting:**

**Main File (server.js):**
- Import router: `require("./routes/posts")`
- Use base path: `app.use('/api/posts', postsRouter)`

**Route File (routes/posts.js):**
- Create router: `express.Router()`
- Define relative paths: `"/"` instead of `"/api/posts"`
- Export router: `module.exports = router`

**Path Matching Explained:**
- `server.js`: `app.use('/api/posts', postsRouter)`
- `posts.js`: `router.get("/")`
- **Result URL**: `/api/posts/` + `/` = `/api/posts`

**Benefits:**
- Better organization
- Easier maintenance
- Team collaboration
- Scalable codebase

**How filter() works:**
- Goes through each item in the array
- Keeps the item if your condition returns `true`
- Removes the item if your condition returns `false`
- Always returns a new array (doesn't modify the original)

**Delete logic with filter():**
```javascript
// To delete an item, keep everything that is NOT the item
posts = posts.filter(post => post.id !== idToDelete);
```

**Key comparison:**
- `!==` ‚Üí keep all other items ‚Üí removes the match (correct for deletion)
- `===` ‚Üí keeps only the match ‚Üí wrong for deletion

**Example:**
```javascript
const posts = [
  { id: 1, title: "First Post" },
  { id: 2, title: "Second Post" },
  { id: 3, title: "Third Post" }
];

// Delete post with id 2
const idToDelete = 2;
const updatedPosts = posts.filter(post => post.id !== idToDelete);

console.log(updatedPosts);
// Output: [{ id: 1, title: "First Post" }, { id: 3, title: "Third Post" }]
```

**Remember:**
- `===` keeps the item you're trying to delete
- `!==` removes the item you're trying to delete
- Filter creates a new array, so assign it back to your variable

**Simple Definition:**
Express provides properties and methods on the `req` (request) object to get information about incoming HTTP requests.

**Request Properties (Data about the request):**
```javascript
// HTTP Method & URL
req.method      // "GET", "POST", "PUT", "DELETE" 
req.protocol    // "http" or "https"
req.originalUrl // "/api/posts/5" (full URL path)
req.path        // "/api/posts/5" (same as originalUrl)
req.params      // { id: "5" } (URL parameters)
req.query       // { limit: "10" } (query string ?limit=10)

// Headers & Host
req.headers     // All request headers
req.get('host') // "localhost:3000" or "mysite.com"
req.hostname    // "localhost" or "mysite.com"

// Security & IP
req.secure      // true if HTTPS, false if HTTP
req.ip          // "192.168.1.1" (client IP address)

// Body data (with body-parser middleware)
req.body        // Parsed request body data
```

**Request Methods (Functions you can call):**
```javascript
// Header methods
req.get('Content-Type')        // Get specific header value
req.is('application/json')     // Check content type

// Parameter methods  
req.param('id')               // Get parameter from URL or query

// Other methods
req.accepts('json')           // Check what formats client accepts
req.accepts(['json', 'html']) // Check multiple formats
```

**Middleware Example Using Properties/Methods:**
```javascript
const logger = (req, res, next) => {
    console.log(`${req.method} ${req.protocol}://${req.get('host')}${req.originalUrl}`);
    // Example output: "GET http://localhost:3000/api/posts/5"
    next();
};

// Route handler example
app.get('/api/users/:id', (req, res) => {
    console.log(req.params.id);    // URL parameter
    console.log(req.query.page);   // Query string
    console.log(req.method);       // HTTP method
    res.json({ success: true });
});
```

**Key Points:**
- **Properties** = Data stored on the request object (use directly)
- **Methods** = Functions you call on the request object (use with parentheses)
- All properties/methods are available in every middleware and route handler

**Key Idea:** Express request properties and methods give you detailed information about incoming HTTP requests, making it easy to build dynamic, responsive web applications.

**Simple Definition:**
HTTP status codes are standardized numbers that tell the client whether a request succeeded or failed, and why.

**Status Code Categories:**
- **200s (Success)**: Request was successful
- **400s (Client Errors)**: User's fault - invalid request
- **500s (Server Errors)**: Server's fault - internal problems

**Success Responses (200s):**
- **200 OK** - Successful GET request
- **201 Created** - New resource created (POST)
- **204 No Content** - Successful delete, no data to return

**Client Errors (400s):**
- **400 Bad Request** - Invalid form data, wrong format
- **401 Unauthorized** - Not logged in
- **403 Forbidden** - Logged in but no permission
- **404 Not Found** - Requested resource doesn't exist

**Server Errors (500s):**
- **500 Internal Server Error** - Database issues, code bugs

**Code Examples:**

**200 OK - Getting Data:**
```javascript
app.get("/api/posts", async (req, res) => {
  try {
    const posts = await db.getPosts();
    res.status(200).json(posts);
  } catch (error) {
    res.status(500).json({ error: "Server error" });
  }
});
```

**201 Created - New Resource:**
```javascript
app.post("/api/posts", async (req, res) => {
  try {
    const { title, content } = req.body;
    const newPost = await db.createPost({ title, content });
    res.status(201).json(newPost);
  } catch (error) {
    res.status(500).json({ error: "Failed to create post" });
  }
});
```

**204 No Content - Successful Delete:**
```javascript
app.delete("/api/posts/:id", async (req, res) => {
  try {
    await db.deletePost(req.params.id);
    res.status(204).send(); // No content to return
  } catch (error) {
    res.status(500).json({ error: "Failed to delete" });
  }
});
```

**400 Bad Request - Invalid Data:**
```javascript
app.post("/api/users", async (req, res) => {
  try {
    const { email, password } = req.body;

    if (!email || !password) {
      return res.status(400).json({ error: "Email and password required" });
    }

    if (password.length < 6) {
      return res.status(400).json({ error: "Password too short" });
    }

    const user = await db.createUser({ email, password });
    res.status(201).json(user);
  } catch (error) {
    res.status(500).json({ error: "Registration failed" });
  }
});
```

**404 Not Found - Resource Doesn't Exist:**
```javascript
app.get("/api/posts/:id", async (req, res) => {
  try {
    const post = await db.getPost(req.params.id);

    if (!post) {
      return res.status(404).json({ error: "Post not found" });
    }

    res.status(200).json(post);
  } catch (error) {
    res.status(500).json({ error: "Server error" });
  }
});
```

**Complete Example with Multiple Status Codes:**
```javascript
app.put("/api/posts/:id", async (req, res) => {
  try {
    const { title, content } = req.body;

    // 400 - Validation
    if (!title || !content) {
      return res.status(400).json({ error: "Title and content required" });
    }

    // 404 - Check if exists
    const existingPost = await db.getPost(req.params.id);
    if (!existingPost) {
      return res.status(404).json({ error: "Post not found" });
    }

    // 403 - Authorization
    if (existingPost.authorId !== req.user.id) {
      return res.status(403).json({ error: "Can only edit your own posts" });
    }

    // 200 - Success
    const updatedPost = await db.updatePost(req.params.id, { title, content });
    res.status(200).json(updatedPost);

  } catch (error) {
    // 500 - Unexpected server error
    res.status(500).json({ error: "Failed to update post" });
  }
});
```

**Key Idea:** Use appropriate HTTP status codes to clearly communicate the result of API requests and handle errors gracefully.

**Simple Definition:**
Organizing backend code into specialized classes that each handle one specific responsibility, following the MVC (Model-View-Controller) pattern.

**üèóÔ∏è Project Structure:**
```
src/
‚îú‚îÄ‚îÄ controllers/     # üéØ Handles HTTP requests/responses
‚îú‚îÄ‚îÄ services/        # üîß Contains business logic
‚îú‚îÄ‚îÄ models/          # üìä Defines data structure
‚îî‚îÄ‚îÄ routes/          # üõ£Ô∏è Maps URLs to controllers
```

**üîß Each Layer's Responsibility:**

**1. Models (Data Structure)**
```javascript
// models/Post.js
class Post {
  constructor(title, content, author) {
    this.title = title;
    this.content = content;
    this.author = author;
    this.createdAt = new Date();
  }

  isValid() {
    return this.title && this.content;
  }
}

module.exports = Post;
```
*Job:* Define data structure and validation

**2. Services (Business Logic)**
```javascript
// services/PostService.js
class PostService {
  constructor() {
    this.posts = [];
  }

  getAllPosts() {
    return this.posts;
  }

  createPost(postData) {
    const newPost = new Post(postData.title, postData.content, postData.author);
    if (!newPost.isValid()) {
      throw new Error("Invalid post data");
    }
    this.posts.push(newPost);
    return newPost;
  }
}
```
*Job:* Handle business rules and data processing

**3. Controllers (HTTP Handling)**
```javascript
// controllers/PostController.js
class PostController {
  constructor() {
    this.postService = new PostService();
  }

  async getPosts(req, res) {
    try {
      const posts = this.postService.getAllPosts();
      res.status(200).json(posts);
    } catch (error) {
      res.status(500).json({ error: error.message });
    }
  }
}
```
*Job:* Manage HTTP requests and responses

**4. Routes (URL Mapping)**
```javascript
// routes/postRoutes.js
const postController = new PostController();

router.get('/posts', postController.getPosts.bind(postController));
router.post('/posts', postController.createPost.bind(postController));
```
*Job:* Direct URLs to appropriate controllers

**üéØ Workflow Example:**

**Request Flow:**
```
POST /api/posts 
‚Üí Routes 
‚Üí PostController.createPost() 
‚Üí PostService.createPost() 
‚Üí Post model
‚Üí Return HTTP response
```

**Code Flow:**
```javascript
// 1. Route receives request
router.post('/posts', postController.createPost);

// 2. Controller handles HTTP
createPost(req, res) {
  const result = this.postService.createPost(req.body);
  res.status(201).json(result);
}

// 3. Service handles business logic
createPost(postData) {
  // Validation, processing, etc.
  return new Post(postData);
}

// 4. Model defines data structure
class Post { ... }
```

**‚úÖ Benefits:**
- **Organization**: Code is logically separated
- **Maintainability**: Easy to find and fix issues
- **Testability**: Services can be tested without HTTP
- **Reusability**: Services work with any interface (API, CLI, etc.)
- **Teamwork**: Different developers can work on different layers

**üîß Restaurant Analogy:**
- **Routes** = Host (directs customers to tables)
- **Controllers** = Waiters (take orders, serve food)
- **Services** = Chefs (cook food, business logic)
- **Models** = Recipes (define how food should be made)

**Key Idea:** Separation of concerns makes your code more organized, maintainable, and scalable by dividing responsibilities into distinct layers.

