**You MUST use `app.use(express.json())` middleware when destructuring `req.body`.**

**Why This Middleware is Essential:**

**Express does NOT parse JSON by default**

When you send a POST request with a JSON body:
```json
{
  "author": "James Carter"
}
```

Express does not automatically convert that JSON into `req.body`.

Without the JSON parser, Express literally receives the raw bytes:
```
7B 20 22 61 75 74 68 6F 72 22 ...
```
Worthless to your controller.

**‚ùå Without express.json():**
```javascript
createBook = (req, res) => {
  console.log(req.body); // undefined

  // Your destructuring will break:
  const { author } = req.body;
  // TypeError: Cannot read properties of undefined
};
```

**‚úÖ With express.json():**
```javascript
app.use(express.json());
```

Now Express converts incoming JSON into a proper JavaScript object:
```javascript
req.body = {
  author: "James Carter"
}
```

Your controller now works:
```javascript
const { author } = req.body; // "James Carter"
```

**üß† Where to Place express.json():**

`server.js` (or `app.js`) is where you configure your Express app before any routes run. Middlewares must be set up first, otherwise your controllers will receive unparsed requests.

**Flow is:**
```
Middleware (parsers, loggers, CORS)
‚Üì
Routes
‚Üì
Controllers
```

**Correct Setup:**
```javascript
// server.js
import express from 'express';

const app = express();

// ‚úÖ MIDDLEWARE FIRST
app.use(express.json());
app.use(express.urlencoded({ extended: true }));

// ‚úÖ THEN ROUTES
app.use('/api/books', bookRoutes);
app.use('/api/users', userRoutes);

// If you put app.use(express.json()) after your routes, 
// it's useless ‚Äî the controllers won't get parsed bodies.
```

**Key Idea:** Always set up `express.json()` middleware BEFORE your routes to properly parse JSON request bodies and enable destructuring of `req.body`.

**Why Hash Passwords?**
- **Security**: Never store plain text passwords
- **Irreversible**: Can't get original password from hash
- **Different hashes**: Same password ‚Üí different hash every time

**Installation:**
```bash
npm install bcryptjs
```

**Basic Usage:**

**1. Hashing Passwords (Registration):**
```javascript
import bcrypt from 'bcryptjs';

// Hash a password
const plainPassword = "user123";
const hashedPassword = bcrypt.hashSync(plainPassword, 10);
// Result: "$2a$10$N9qo8uLOickgx2ZMRZoMye..."

// Store hashedPassword in database instead of plain text
```

**2. Verifying Passwords (Login):**
```javascript
// When user tries to login
const isPasswordValid = bcrypt.compareSync("user123", hashedPassword);
// Returns: true (if correct) or false (if wrong)
```

**In UserService Class:**
```javascript
class UserService {
  constructor() {
    this.users = [];
  }

  registerUser(userData) {
    const { email, password } = userData;

    // Hash before storing
    const hashedPassword = bcrypt.hashSync(password, 10);

    const user = {
      id: this.users.length + 1,
      email: email,
      password: hashedPassword, // Store the hash!
      createdAt: new Date()
    };

    this.users.push(user);
    return user;
  }

  loginUser(email, password) {
    const user = this.users.find(u => u.email === email);
    if (!user) {
      throw new Error("User not found");
    }

    // Verify password
    const isValid = bcrypt.compareSync(password, user.password);
    if (!isValid) {
      throw new Error("Invalid password");
    }

    return user; // Login successful
  }

  findUserByEmail(email) {
    return this.users.find(u => u.email === email);
  }
}
```

**Async/Await Version (Recommended):**
```javascript
class UserService {
  async registerUser(userData) {
    const { email, password } = userData;

    // Hash with async/await
    const hashedPassword = await bcrypt.hash(password, 10);

    const user = {
      email: email,
      password: hashedPassword,
    };

    return user;
  }

  async loginUser(email, password) {
    const user = this.findUserByEmail(email);
    if (!user) {
      throw new Error("User not found");
    }

    // Verify with async/await
    const isValid = await bcrypt.compare(password, user.password);
    if (!isValid) {
      throw new Error("Invalid password");
    }

    return user;
  }
}
```

**Key Points:**
- **Salt Rounds (10)**: Higher = more secure but slower (10-12 is recommended)
- **compareSync()**: Checks if password matches hash
- **Never store plain passwords** in database
- **Never return passwords** in API responses
- Use **async methods** (`bcrypt.hash()` and `bcrypt.compare()`) in production for better performance

**Security Benefits:**
- ‚úÖ Same password ‚Üí different hashes (due to unique salt)
- ‚úÖ Slow hashing prevents brute force attacks
- ‚úÖ Can't reverse engineer passwords from hashes
- ‚úÖ Protects users even if database is compromised

**Use this for ALL user authentication! üõ°Ô∏è**
